    <annotation id="prefigure-gr3b-sample-figure" speech2="The graph is a rational function separated into two branches by the vertical                        asymptote at x=1. The graph has an oblique asymptote at y=-\frac{1}{2}x+1. The graph                        passes through the origin (0,0) which is both the x-intercept and y-intercept. For x less than 1,                        the graph is below the oblique asymptote and approaches the vertical asymptote at x=1 toward                        negative infinity. For 1 greater than x, the graph is above the oblique asymptote and approaches                        the vertical asymptote at x=1 toward positive infinity. As x approaches positive or negative                        infinity, the graph approaches the oblique asymptote y=-\frac{1}{2}x+1.">
